{
  "Producers are also called:": "",
  "Heterotrophs, because they consume other organisms to obtain their energy and nutrients": "",
  "Autotrophs, because they make their own food from inorganic molecules": "",
  "Apex predators, because they regulate population sizes at the top of food chains": "",
  "Decomposers, because they recycle dead material back into usable soil nutrients": "",
  "Producers are autotrophs, meaning they synthesize their own food through photosynthesis or chemosynthesis, converting inorganic molecules into organic compounds that form the base of food webs.": "",
  "The primary source of energy for most ecosystems on Earth is:": "",
  "Wind energy, which drives atmospheric circulation and distributes heat across ecosystems": "",
  "Sunlight, which is captured by producers through photosynthesis": "",
  "Lightning, which triggers chemical reactions in the atmosphere and ignites natural fires": "",
  "Geothermal heat, which warms underground water systems and volcanic soil environments": "",
  "Sunlight is the primary energy source for nearly all ecosystems on Earth, as producers (plants, algae, cyanobacteria) capture solar energy through photosynthesis to power food webs.": "",
  "Primary consumers feed directly on:": "",
  "Producers (plants and algae)": "",
  "Sunlight directly": "",
  "Decomposers only": "",
  "Other animals only": "",
  "Primary consumers are herbivores that feed directly on producers, occupying the second trophic level in a food chain and transferring energy from plants to the rest of the food web.": "",
  "Secondary consumers are organisms that:": "",
  "Eat only plants": "",
  "Only decompose dead matter": "",
  "Eat primary consumers (herbivores)": "",
  "Produce their own food": "",
  "Secondary consumers are carnivores or omnivores that feed on primary consumers (herbivores), occupying the third trophic level and further transferring energy through the food web.": "",
  "Decomposers are essential to ecosystems because they:": "",
  "Only eat living organisms": "",
  "Are the top predators in food chains": "",
  "Produce oxygen through photosynthesis": "",
  "Break down dead organic matter and recycle nutrients back into the ecosystem": "",
  "Decomposers like bacteria and fungi break down dead organisms and waste, releasing nutrients back into the soil and atmosphere, which allows producers to use them again in a continuous cycle.": "",
  "Abiotic factors in an ecosystem include:": "",
  "Only bacteria and fungi": "",
  "Nonliving components such as temperature, water, sunlight, and soil": "",
  "Only the animals present": "",
  "Only the plants present": "",
  "Abiotic factors are the nonliving physical and chemical components of an ecosystem, including temperature, precipitation, sunlight, soil type, and pH, which strongly influence which organisms can survive.": "",
  "Biotic factors in an ecosystem include:": "",
  "Only temperature and rainfall": "",
  "Only rocks and minerals": "",
  "All living organisms and their interactions": "",
  "Only sunlight and wind": "",
  "Biotic factors include all living organisms in an ecosystem, such as plants, animals, fungi, and bacteria, along with their interactions like predation, competition, and symbiosis.": "",
  "An omnivore is an organism that:": "",
  "Eats only plants": "",
  "Eats only meat": "",
  "Eats both plants and animals": "",
  "Only decomposes dead matter": "",
  "Omnivores consume both plant and animal material, which means they can occupy multiple trophic levels in food webs. Examples include bears, humans, and raccoons.": "",
  "Tertiary consumers are typically:": "",
  "Herbivores that eat only plant material": "",
  "Producers that create their own food": "",
  "Decomposers that break down waste matter": "",
  "Top predators that eat secondary consumers": "",
  "Tertiary consumers are top predators at the fourth trophic level that feed on secondary consumers. Examples include eagles eating snakes that eat mice, or sharks eating fish that eat smaller fish.": "",
  "Which of the following is an example of a producer?": "",
  "A hawk that hunts smaller animals": "",
  "A mushroom that decomposes matter": "",
  "A green plant performing photosynthesis": "",
  "A deer that grazes on vegetation": "",
  "Green plants are producers because they use photosynthesis to convert sunlight, carbon dioxide, and water into glucose and oxygen, creating the food and energy base for ecosystems.": "",
  "What is photosynthesis?": "",
  "The process by which producers convert sunlight, CO2, and water into glucose and oxygen": "",
  "The process of breaking down dead organisms": "",
  "The release of energy from food by consumers": "",
  "The movement of water through soil": "",
  "Photosynthesis is the process by which plants, algae, and some bacteria use sunlight energy to convert carbon dioxide and water into glucose (food energy) and oxygen as a byproduct.": "",
  "What is a trophic level?": "",
  "A category of tropical ecosystem defined by its climate and vegetation patterns": "",
  "A distinct layer within soil profiles that differs in mineral composition and texture": "",
  "A standardized measurement of water temperature used in aquatic ecological research": "",
  "A feeding position in a food chain or food web that indicates an organism's energy source": "",
  "A trophic level represents each step in a food chain where energy is transferred, from producers (level 1) through primary consumers (level 2), secondary consumers (level 3), and so on.": "",
  "What is cellular respiration?": "",
  "A metabolic pathway found exclusively in plant cells during periods of active growth": "",
  "The process by which organisms break down glucose to release energy (ATP), consuming oxygen and producing CO2": "",
  "The geological process by which rocks are chemically broken down into sediment layers": "",
  "The physiological act of breathing, involving the exchange of gases in the lungs": "",
  "Cellular respiration is the metabolic process in which cells break down glucose using oxygen to produce ATP (usable energy), carbon dioxide, and water, occurring in all living organisms.": "",
  "What is a detritivore?": "",
  "A type of autotrophic producer that generates energy through photosynthesis in aquatic systems": "",
  "An organism that exclusively feeds on living plant tissue and young shoots in forests": "",
  "An organism that eats detritus (dead organic matter) such as earthworms and millipedes": "",
  "A carnivorous predator that actively hunts and captures live prey in terrestrial habitats": "",
  "Detritivores are organisms that consume dead organic matter (detritus), physically breaking it down into smaller pieces. Examples include earthworms, millipedes, and dung beetles.": "",
  "What is chemosynthesis?": "",
  "The geological process by which rocks are chemically weathered and broken down into soil minerals": "",
  "The process by which some organisms produce food using chemical energy from inorganic compounds instead of sunlight": "",
  "A laboratory synthesis technique used exclusively for creating compounds in controlled settings": "",
  "A specialized form of aerobic cellular respiration that occurs only in mitochondrial membranes": "",
  "Chemosynthesis is an alternative to photosynthesis used by certain bacteria to produce food energy from inorganic chemicals like hydrogen sulfide, supporting ecosystems in deep-sea hydrothermal vents.": "",
  "What is a herbivore?": "",
  "An organism that feeds exclusively on plants or other producers": "",
  "An organism that only eats other animals": "",
  "An organism that produces its own food": "",
  "An organism that decomposes dead matter": "",
  "A herbivore is an animal that feeds exclusively on plants or other producers, serving as a primary consumer and forming a critical link between producers and higher-level consumers in food webs.": "",
  "What is a heterotroph?": "",
  "A nonliving component of an ecosystem": "",
  "An organism that cannot make its own food and must obtain energy by consuming other organisms": "",
  "A type of rock formation": "",
  "An organism that makes its own food": "",
  "Heterotrophs are organisms that cannot produce their own food and must consume other organisms for energy. All consumers and decomposers are heterotrophs.": "",
  "What is a scavenger?": "",
  "A type of producer": "",
  "An organism that hunts and kills its prey": "",
  "An organism that feeds on the carcasses of dead animals it did not kill": "",
  "An organism that only eats plants": "",
  "Scavengers are animals that consume dead organisms they did not kill, such as vultures and hyenas. They play an important role in ecosystems by helping recycle nutrients from dead animals.": "",
  "What is an apex predator?": "",
  "Any animal that eats plants": "",
  "A decomposer at the bottom of the food chain": "",
  "A primary consumer": "",
  "A predator at the top of the food chain with no natural predators of its own": "",
  "An apex predator sits at the top of a food chain with no natural predators, such as wolves, sharks, or eagles. They help regulate populations of prey species and maintain ecosystem balance.": "",
  "What is biomass?": "",
  "The total area of an ecosystem": "",
  "The weight of rocks in an area": "",
  "The total mass of living organic matter in an ecosystem or at a specific trophic level": "",
  "The amount of water in a lake": "",
  "Biomass is the total mass of living organic material at a given trophic level or in an ecosystem, typically measured in grams per square meter. It decreases at each higher trophic level.": "",
  "In a pond ecosystem, algae populations suddenly crash due to a drought that reduces water levels. What would you predict happens to the zooplankton (tiny animals) that feed on the algae?": "",
  "Zooplankton would switch to photosynthesis": "",
  "Zooplankton populations would increase because they have less competition": "",
  "Zooplankton populations would decline because their food source (producers) has been reduced": "",
  "Zooplankton populations would be unaffected": "",
  "When producer populations decline, primary consumers that depend on them for food will also decline due to reduced food availability, demonstrating how energy flows upward through trophic levels.": "",
  "A farmer notices that after clearing all the leaf litter and fallen branches from a forest floor, the soil becomes less fertile over time. This is most likely because:": "",
  "Removing dead organic matter deprives decomposers of material to break down and return nutrients to the soil": "",
  "Animals have left the area permanently": "",
  "Sunlight is no longer reaching the soil": "",
  "The trees are producing too much oxygen": "",
  "Decomposers break down leaf litter and dead wood, releasing nutrients back into the soil for producers. Removing this material disrupts the nutrient cycle and leads to soil nutrient depletion.": "",
  "In a grassland ecosystem, a disease kills most of the rabbit population. What would most likely happen to the fox population that preys on rabbits and the grass population that rabbits eat?": "",
  "Both populations decrease simultaneously": "",
  "Fox population increases and grass population decreases": "",
  "Fox population decreases (less prey) and grass population increases (less grazing)": "",
  "Both populations remain unchanged": "",
  "Removing a primary consumer (rabbits) causes its predator (foxes) to decline from food scarcity while its food source (grass) increases from reduced grazing pressure, showing interconnected trophic relationships.": "",
  "Scientists discover thriving communities of organisms around deep-sea hydrothermal vents where no sunlight reaches. The base of this food web is most likely supported by:": "",
  "Photosynthetic algae that drifted down from the surface": "",
  "Decomposers that feed on dead whales": "",
  "Animals that eat rocks from the ocean floor": "",
  "Chemosynthetic bacteria that use chemical energy from hydrogen sulfide to produce food": "",
  "Deep-sea hydrothermal vent communities are based on chemosynthetic bacteria that use the chemical energy in hydrogen sulfide to produce organic compounds, serving as producers without sunlight.": "",
  "A lake receives excessive nutrient runoff from nearby farms, causing massive algae blooms. When the algae die, decomposer populations explode, consuming most of the dissolved oxygen. Fish begin dying. This sequence illustrates:": "",
  "That algae are always bad for lakes": "",
  "That decomposers are harmful organisms that should be removed": "",
  "That fish cannot survive in freshwater": "",
  "How an imbalance in one part of an ecosystem (excess nutrients) can cascade through producers, decomposers, and consumers": "",
  "This eutrophication scenario shows how nutrient excess triggers algal blooms, whose decomposition depletes oxygen, killing fish. It demonstrates the interconnected roles of producers, decomposers, and consumers.": "",
  "A coral reef ecosystem has producers (algae), primary consumers (parrotfish), secondary consumers (grouper), and decomposers (bacteria). If a new disease kills most of the coral algae, the most likely cascade effect would be:": "",
  "Only the parrotfish populations would decline because they directly depend on the coral algae": "",
  "Populations at all consumer levels would eventually decline because the energy base of the ecosystem has been reduced": "",
  "Decomposer bacteria would shift their role and become the new primary producers for the reef": "",
  "Grouper populations would actually increase because reduced competition frees up habitat space": "",
  "Losing the producers (algae) removes the energy base of the food web, causing cascading declines through all trophic levels because each level depends on energy transferred from the level below.": "",
  "A student observes that a compost bin in the school garden turns food scraps into rich soil over several weeks. The organisms most responsible for this transformation are:": "",
  "Primary consumers that graze on the compost": "",
  "Decomposers including bacteria, fungi, and detritivores that break down organic matter into nutrients": "",
  "Apex predators that consume the waste": "",
  "Producers that photosynthesize the scraps into soil": "",
  "Composting relies on decomposers (bacteria, fungi) and detritivores (earthworms, insects) to break down organic waste into nutrient-rich humus, mimicking the natural decomposition process in ecosystems.": "",
  "In the Arctic Ocean, tiny phytoplankton produce food through photosynthesis, supporting krill, which are eaten by fish, which are eaten by seals, which are eaten by polar bears. If climate change reduces sea ice, causing phytoplankton to decline, the effect on polar bears would be:": "",
  "Polar bear populations would eventually decline because reduced producer biomass means less energy flows to top predators": "",
  "No effect, since polar bears do not eat phytoplankton directly": "",
  "Polar bears would switch to photosynthesis": "",
  "Polar bear populations would increase as competition decreases": "",
  "Even though polar bears are far removed from phytoplankton in the food chain, they depend on the energy flow that starts with producers. A decline in phytoplankton cascades through every trophic level.": "",
  "A garden has plants, caterpillars, birds, and decomposing leaf litter with fungi. A gardener removes all the fungi and microorganisms from the soil. Over time, the plants begin to grow poorly. This is because:": "",
  "Fungi and decomposers were physically blocking the sunlight from reaching the plant leaf surfaces": "",
  "Without decomposers to recycle nutrients from dead matter, the soil loses fertility and plants cannot get the nutrients they need": "",
  "Caterpillar populations became more aggressive and consumed significantly more plant tissue overall": "",
  "The birds consumed all the remaining available mineral nutrients directly from the topsoil layer": "",
  "Decomposers are essential for nutrient recycling. Without fungi and bacteria breaking down dead matter, nutrients remain locked in organic material and are unavailable to plants.": "",
  "A marine biologist studying a tropical ocean ecosystem finds that removing the top predator (large sharks) leads to an explosion of mid-level predators (small sharks), which overeat herbivorous fish, allowing algae to overgrow and smother coral reefs. This series of events is called:": "",
  "Primary succession, where bare rock is gradually colonized by pioneer species over many decades": "",
  "Decomposition, where organic material is broken down by bacteria and fungi into simple compounds": "",
  "A trophic cascade, where removing one trophic level causes ripple effects through the entire food web": "",
  "Photosynthesis, where producers convert sunlight and carbon dioxide into glucose and oxygen molecules": "",
  "A trophic cascade occurs when a change at one trophic level triggers a chain reaction through other levels. Removing apex predators can destabilize entire ecosystems by allowing populations below them to shift dramatically.": ""
}